,Recommended,307960,34920020,Posted: 13 September,all,-OrLoK-,"TL;DR: Brilliant WW2 Flight Sim. All the old bugbears have been taken out. goes on regular 50pc sale. Well worth a peek.Long ramble below....Hello thereI dont often write reviews as there are others far more adept to that than I. But Here goes...Im an old *original* Il2 player and a fan of all the off-shoots and rivals of the genre.So, when Battke of Stalingrad was released I was very keen to take a look.However, like many, I was (incorrectly) expecting an upgraded version of IL2 and it's oodles of content. That and the Premium plane puchaces seemed ""odd"" to my sensibilities.So, for a couple of years I shelved the sereies (and the genre) and tootled off to do other stuff.Fast forward a few years and I got the sim bug again and fiddled with War Thunder, which initially was impressive. But the pay to win aspect as well as the ""wobbly plane"" lack of fine controlability became too much for me and I looked elsewhere.Coincidentally, the BoX (ie BoS,BoM,BoK etc) was on one of it's regular 50pc sales so i snaffled up BoS for 25 quid.Comming from Il2/DCS etc and not wanting an arcadey experience I initially balked at some design aspects and interface decisions of BoS (as well as the premium plane shop).But after spending some time with the game and seeing massive improvements the devs had implemented and knowing of upcoming changes to the series, I can now understand many of the choices the devs have made, which at the time felt so alien and ""wrong"" but are actually simply ""different"" and have their own value.The ""Premium"" planes were renamed as ""Collector"" planes as that's exactly what they are. They're not needed nor are they pay to win as each is very quirky and by no means a beast rather are for enthusiasts.The unlock system for extra weapon pods/extras has now been removed (which I actually rather liked) and the Visual options has been greatly expanded.To name but a few examplesFor me, the series has now reached maturity and is an essential purchace for any avid ww2/flight simmer.Are the games pricey in comparison to other mainstream games? Yes. But these guys are in a niche market and producing incredibly high quality content. WT planes and flight models are in no way comparable.But, as I mentioned there are regular huge sales (up to 50pc off) and for those unsure are a great way to get your feet wet.There are no ""clicky"" pits and as a DCS player I originally thought this  would be a turn off. In actual fact , for me, its a boon as the engine control management is more than enough to concentrate on whilst in flight over clicking about the cockpit. others will feel differently but in BoX, I dont miss it. YMMV.Now, what converted me utterly is BoX's VR support. It's not perfect (what VR game is?) but it *is* astounding.The pits really come to life and I cant go back to my trackir 5 and 3 monitors (6400x1080) any more. VR just blows them away.I feel ""there"".Indeed ive often tried to physically use pull bars or adjust something with my hands for a second or two before realising im not really in the cockpit.Now, the game isnt perfect but it's damn close. As development goes on I find less and less to gripe about as the pros simply outweigh any cons at this stage.I know own the entire series as well as all the ""collector"" planes. I often simply fly to just fly and dont always need combat to spice things up.The planned Pacific setting for the next expansion is exciting and there's more major changes planned from the new campaign system to the introduction of modding.This game isnt for the uber casual but if one does play WT with as Stick/Hotas then this series is well worth investigating. It's mnot a study im like DCS either but has more than enough complexity to keep the most ardent of button pushers happy.Its also a hugely pretty game and still keep surprising me.If you have the pennies, get it...get it all. If not wait for a sale, I dont think you'll be dissapointed.RgdsLoK"
