ystick w/throttle-requires rudder pedals (or twist axis on stick)-requires head tracking (if dog fighting at least)-the official website offers more content to buy than steam-steam and non-steam DLCs or ""collector planes"" work together fine-The Battle of _____ ""DLCS"" should really be called expansions, remember those?-Consult the official site with an easier layout to understand what planes you get with what ""battle of _____ "" ect-I use a FX8350, GTX970, 16 gigs of ram, non SSD system and this game runs fine with settings maxed out. Sitting at the airfield with a BUNCH of stuff going on will make me lose significant amount of frames, but it's irrelevant to me since it's a non-combat situation."
,Recommended,307960,33669546,Posted: 20 July,all,Jordan,"A few things to me first: I only recently added this game to my steam library but I have played it somewhere between 1000 and 1500 hours in the last 3.5 years. I played civil flightsims from X-plane over to all microsoft flight simulators starting from Fs95 as well as combat flight simulators as CFS1/2/3, Il-2 1946 and Il-2 CloD.To me it is a bit uncomprehensible that this game is receiving so many negative reviews. In my eyes this sim has many bits that make it unique. (As have DCS, CloD etc.)I will not list pros and cons as it  not quite fit my scheme here, instead I will talk about features and issues.- Advanced flight model:Il-2s flight model is dynamic, this means that there is no generic flight model that gets adjusted for every plane but the parts of a plane themselves have aerodynamic properties and all of them combined create the planes’ motion of flight (only X-Plane has this too). With an AFM each plane behaves unique but the workload to create such a flight model is a lot higher than with a standard static flight model. As all parts need to work together to create the required results, in raw numbers, a static flight model is likely to get closer to the referenced resources. Il-2 has a set margin of error of 5% for their flight models, but in general the resulting error does seldom exceed more than 2%. Although being a bit less accurate in the numbers department an AFM can create an infinite amount of flight-situations depending on all kind of dynamic parameters. (e.g. different stall conditions).- The game world:Il-2 comes with carefully created maps for each theater (BoS/ BoM /BoK soon) as well as some smaller maps that are untied to a scenario (Lapino map / Novoskolniki map). The maps have been thoroughly researched and created close to the 1940s appearance (for example the Don river reservoir had not been created in the 1940s and is thus missing ingame). Both Stalingrad (360x230km) and BoM (280x280km) maps are so big that seeing every part of it would need dozens of hours of flying on them. The maps, objects, weather and lighting are (in my eyes) very well matched to each other and create a very immersive and often beautiful scenery.- The planesets and planes:The planesets have been created to recreate the common planeset of that theater for a specific time (exceptions Mc202 and Fw-190-A3). All models are modeled close to historic sources. (and fixed if at fault). The systemsmodelling of Il-2 is not as advanced as lets say DCS, but it is quite detailed nevertheless. All engines behave specific to their properties (there is no generic engine model).What is missing for me is advanced fuel management and fuel systems modeling (on the dev list though).-The career:Right now there is a rather numb career mode that is a bit out of sync with the rest of the sim although its core is well developed. This comes as a big minus for many simmers and I can absolutely understand this. BUT: The Il-2 team is working hard on creating a dynamic career mode that is both close to history as well as individually immersive and expected to exceed the Rise of Flight campaign system which is already pretty good. In the new career mode it will also be possible to start in BoM (1941) and flying with your squadron all the way through BoS (1942/43) to BoK (1943). It's expected to be released in Q4 2017.- Flight model update Q3 2017:The currect AFM of this game has one distinctive problem: oscillations, especially in pitching and yaw-ing movements. At the end of 2016 the developers announced that they had gained further knowledge on specific behavior of planes in certain flight conditions and that they were reworking all flight models to match even closer to reality. This patch is expected to arrive by the end of August 2017. (together with BoK map)- Tuturials: Yeah, sadly there are none yet – you need to visit the forums or youtube to get your informations and suggestions on how to fly.- Pricing policy:It is often claimed that this game is exceedingly expensive for the content it offers or that the developers are being greedy. I can In no way relate to this. Working with software myself I can see how much work has gone into this sim.  The flight sim genre is small nowadays and developers struggle to make a living. (You don't produce a flightsime for money) Its not just graphics that make a game, all the modelling that is in this game is what makes it so expensive (also consider that a plane-model in 1946 Il-2 required about 10 times less effort). Just keep that in mind. Yes it is not cheap but you get something very close to reality on your home computer for 50 bucks which is a sensation in itself.As for registration: please follow the steps listed after purchasing this game and activate you key at the il2 website. (This game was not created with steam in mind) If there are any issues you can file a support ticket in your il2 websites profile.I can definitely recommend getting this game if you are interested in flight and simulations, be warned though, the learing curve is steep!Hope this review helped some of you! :)"
76561198047621393,Recommended,307960,16099973,"Posted: 31 May, 2015",all,Wolf8312,"A truly excellent flight sim that I have just upgraded to premium as new user content has now become available. I am seriously loving this game and with Ciffs of dover, DCS, and rise of flight all on my computer can just not tear myself away from how much I enjoy the feeling of flying and fighting with these planes.Game's future is dependent upon the support of the community, so please think twice before shooting us all in the foot by slamming this game, as what the game lacks now it will very possibly have in the future, as long as the devs are not in the meantime driven out of business by all the negative reviews.Flight sims are not built in a day!"
