,Recommended,307960,20419941,"Posted: 9 January, 2016",all,Skeleboners,"IL-2 BoS is sort of like War Thunder minus all the things I hated about War Thunder.That's going to be controversial, because a lot of people are posting reviews doing everything they can to prove that IL-2 is //NOTHING!!!// like War Thunder... but it is. And that's not a bad thing!BoS hits the same ""accessible realism"" point that something like War Thunder (mainly sim mode, but ""normal"" settings in BoS include markers and automatic engine management) hits. Neither are the rivet-counting, absolute to the metal fidelity that something like DCS strives to be (I play a lot of DCS too, by the by), but both War Thunder (outside of arcade battles) and BoS are VERY far from the more arcadey, easy to learn experience that an air combat game like Crimson Skies might be. BoS even has an experimental mouse-aim mode for potential aviators who don't have joysticks, though from what I understand the implementation is very rough around the edges at the moment.The main differences in BoS and War Thunder are why I much prefer the former to the latter. War Thunder's primary problems are the free-to-play grind that you have to expect from... well, a free-to-play game (BoS has a progression system that is a tooooouch grindy, as well, but none of the unlocks are really game changing and you can grind them out in singleplayer if you want), and the very questionable flight models and balancing that everyone just sort of accepts as standard from the game now. In BoS, you won't be clubbed by a fighter that's severely over-performing, and you won't be crippled for flying an aircraft you enjoy because it under-performs or finds itself facing unreasonably stiff opposition. Honestly, in BoS, most of the (fighter) aircraft are pretty evenly matched- even the premiums (I fear the 109 pilot over the 190). I've even had semi-successful engagements flying a goddamned IL-2 up against fighters, because at the end of the day a skilled pilot (which I am not- hence the SEMI-successful nature of those engagements) will win no matter his aircraft... and the IL-2 has much better low speed performance than any fighter in the game so dragging♥♥♥♥♥♥sure Bubi-wannabes into low-speed duels is a very good way to embarass the Luftwaffe.All these comparisons to War Thunder aside- you will need a joystick to fully enjoy IL-2: BoS. Preferably one with a rudder axis (Rudder is SUPER IMPORTANT on these old prop aircraft for managing sideslip) and a throttle flapper. You can find a stick like that for like $15-$20, usually. Also, some form of headtracking makes dogfighting, especially on full-realism servers without markets, MUCH easier (maintaining situational awareness is a big part of being a successful combat pilot)- you can build a headtracker with rudimentary knowledge of how to solder and about $30 in materials, or if you have an android smartphone I hear that there are ways to use that, strapped to a headset or something, to get 3-DOF (as in, you won't be able to lean around in the cockpit, but you can look left and right and up and down) headtracking that works decently well. If you're not able or willing to do any of those, you can map your view controls to a hat on your joystick or something, and that should be serviceable.So yeah- If you enjoyed War Thunder when it wasn't harassing you with awful game design and sketchy as frig flight models, and you're okay with a more limited roster of flyable aircraft, AND you're okay with flying with a joystick (until the devs polish mouse aim), pick this game up. It's enormous fun, even flying ground attack or a bomber like the Peshka or the Heinkel (though I do wish you could get magnetic bearing to target in those aircraft, flying bombing approaches on smaller targets without it is a pain in the♥♥♥♥♥♥, and you'll end every fight with a dumb grin even if its you who ended up a fiery ball of dead airplane on the ground. And if you're more a study-sim guy (like I am, honestly), don't gloss over BoS as just-another-WWII-plane-game, it's plenty realistic enough that really only noncombat systems are streamlined (and radios, but we all know you fly with easy communication on in DCS, anyway)."
76561198025743151,Recommended,307960,19348595,"Posted: 28 November, 2015",all,Bio-Rhöni,"Pros:+true combat flight sim experience+reasonably well graphics for a modern flight simulation+great sound and damage effects+authentic flight models and no russian bias like in other russian made ""simulations""+actively played on multiplayer+still in devellopement: with ""Battle of Moscow"" and later probably more DLC's comming upthis game will stay in the attention focus of players and will be part of something bigger in the future.Cons:-Very demanding on pc's performance espacially the CPU-There are issues with the view range. You won't see planes that are further away then 10km at alland everything further then 3km is very hard to spot.-The singleplayer campaign is pretty liveless and boring (they are improving it though)-No clickable cockpits like in ""Cliffs of Dover""A few words on the pricing and DLC politics:If you think Battle of Stalingrad is expensive keep in minde that producing flight sims is at least as expensive if not more expensive then producing a mainstream game that is supposed to be bought by houndred thousands players.But flight sims aren't bought by houndred thousands players as the playerbase for such titles is quite small.Thus the ""high"" price.Even though I can understand that the company needs to make money with the game I think cutting out planes from the game isn't the best solution (Fw-190/La-5) but at least those planes aren't ""pay to win"" in the multiplayer.My recomendation: If you want these planes, simply wait for a sale to get them cheaper.The splitting of the game in big DLC's and working on them one after another to add to a greater game is in my oppinion a great idea.  For one: this makes sure that every single part of the game is finished in a state that actually can be called finished. Flight sims are prone for bugs and flight models that are simply a bit off. Thats why they need time to ""grow the beard"". By splitting the project in peaces the game gets time to do that. (Think of what happened to Cliffs of Dover: Big game, took to long and cost to much money to finish and was rushed to the marked in a horrible state.)For now the patches of ""Battle of Moscow"" with its planes are allready integrated in ""Battle of Stalingrad"" even if you haven't purchased BoM. The only difference is, that you will not be able to fly its planes  untill you buy BoM. Still you will come across BoM's planes in singleplayer and multiplayers as allies and opponents.All in all I think Battle of Stalingrad is a fun flight sim with a promising future.(Fun enough to be a reason for me to replace my stoneage CPU)"
