76561197984324501,Not Recommended,307960,23605597,"Posted: 16 June, 2016",all,xvii-Dietrich,"TLDR: IL-2 Battle of Stalingrad is fairly limited, has a dull single-player campaign, and a poor multiplayer environment. The flight models are good, but the environment, graphics and sounds feel flat. It feels like a chore to play it.Full review: IL-2 Battle of Stalingrad (IL2:BoS) is a flight simulator set on the Eastern Front at the turning point of the Second World War. The battle and backdrop are epic, but this simulator does not do it justice. Technically, the game engine is pretty good, and the simulation of the flight, damage and world environment are actually quite good. However, the interface, presentation and engagement with the player are poor.There are a limited 8 aircraft in the game that you can fly, with a further two available as premium extras for purchase. Some of these are very similar (e.g. two variants of the Bf 109), making it feel even more limited. The implementations are okay, but there are some bugs which greatly detract from the experience. For example, there is a constantly flashing warning message telling you to retract the landing gear... on a Stuka (an aircraft with fixed undercarriage)! The aircraft have various degrees of automation, which I found frustrating. Another example is that the official paint-schemes are just a random assortment from throughout the war... such as desert camouflage in the Soviet Winter. Again, it doesn't stop gameplay, but it is detracting and unnecessary. Also, many of the interesting systems (radios, radar, navigations, etc.) are not implemented.The graphics are fairly flat, making it feel cartoon-like. The icons/interface overlay is cluttered and confusing. The sounds are okay, but the radio messages sound very repetitive and stilted (like badly automated railway announcements). There are also modern ""beep"" sounds, which detract from the ambiance.There is a multiplayer scene, but it is a bit quiet and lacking depth. However, the real let down is the single-player campaign. Rather than a career, where you can follow the progress of the squadron, get promotion, look after an individual aircraft and feel a sense of being there... the campaign is just a string of missions that feel randomly generated. There is some text and the missions work in themselves, but they feel very canned and lacking in depth. It is difficult to feel committed to them. Yes, there is an overall pilot rank and medals, but they are just for the gamer, and not for each individual career or aircraft.Even the ""unlock system"" is weak. I know that some players hate them. To the contrary, I actually really like the unlocks. It gives you a sense of accomplishing something. However, these unlocks are a bit dull. Just extra bombs or new paintschemes, and it is often possible to bag several at once, removing the sense of accomplishment.Although I've had this title for quite some time, and have an interest in the Eastern Front due to personal connection, I simply have not had any enthusiasm for this title. Given its age, it has already matured, so no significant development can be expected to improve the situation. For an arcade player, there are far more extensive titles. For the hard-core simulator enthusiast, IL2:BoS falls short.I do not recommend this title."
76561198037763622,Recommended,307960,31271717,Posted: 21 April,all,snipp5,"Amazing  game  with details , Updates all the time,  Good work and good DLC :)"
76561198099640663,Recommended,307960,12396603,"Posted: 6 October, 2014",all,SAG,"This game has come a long long way since i bought it back in 2014, the graphics have improved, the unlock system is long gone and performance has come a long way as well, and it is now in VR!!! :DThe feeling of flying is the best i've gotten in years of flight simming and it is the most rewarding experience ive had in the gaming world. its  a SIM so don't expect to learn everything in 20 minutes of playing. in fact, don't expect to learn every single aspect of every plane unless you spend a ton of time with them. i have almost 1000 hours on steam and dont know how many on the standalone launcher and that is flying Allied planes almost exlusively.While this game does not have ClickPits like DCS, it does have all the actual complexity of what someone would expect from a WWII flight simulator. You need to watch your engines from overheating or over-reving, adjust your mixture, set supercharger stages, be mindful of your energy, etc. and with the new revised flight model it is even better at giving you the feeling of flying than it was before.The game is playable on a mouse and keyboard but a simple Joystick is necessary IMHO for most people to actually enjoy the title, there are some things that aren't perfect though, like the current campaign which can be a little boring. luckily this is getting overhauled to be more like Rise of Flight's, which has a dynamic campaign where you follow your pilot and his progress through the war.Battle of Stallingrad is a standalone product, just like its stand-alone expansions Battle of Moscow and Battle of Kuban (EA) that are sold thorugh their website and are all integrated into the same launcher (so if you purchase BoS here, you can purchase the rest through the website and have it integrated into steam's BoS launcher). i just clear this up since some people get confused by it. BoM shows in steam as DLC but its actually a standalone expansion that can be purchased in the website; so is Battle of Kuban early access.The game has its flaws like not having a tutorial and considering that it is a game SIMULATING real WWII aircraft, it can be pretty hard for  newcomers to get things going for them. the community makes up for this though with great tutorials and manuals both in written and YT video format which can all be found in the forums.A great thing about having all titles integrated into the same launcher is that all games (BoS, BoM and the new BoK) get upgraded when new improvements are developed for their engine, so VR for example is available for all titles despite only being released during the Battle of Kuban early access. so all the good stuff that is comming for Battle of Kuban is also going to trickle down into the older titles BoS and BoM.Multiplayer is where the more competitive players dwell and where i find myself 90% of the time. it is very rewarding participating in dynamic wars like in the TAW server or to just join a duel server like Berloga for a quick dogfight to sharpen your skills. the Multiplayer server browser is pretty bare-bones so there is no queueing system so if many players are trying to get into the server at once (like when a server restarts) it might take you several tries to get in.If you're going Multiplayer make sure you join people on TeamSpeak or any of the Discord channels, since flying against humans can be quite a challenge!I just wrote my thoughts on the current state of the game since my last review was from 2014 (if i remember correctly) and things have come a long way since.if you want the best WWII flight SIM out there with what is possibly the best VR implementation and a great community, get this game, i personally couldnt recommend it enough! :D"
76561197970875686,Recommended,307960,34891169,Posted: 11 September,all,Draknar986,"Update -Whether I would recommend this game to the general masses I am still on the fence about. Typically, for cheaper games, I'm not as concerned about voting ""yes"", because if it's not quite to someone's palate it's not a major loss, This game is pricey, however, and knowing that I would recommend it to some of my personal friends, and not others, makes it more difficult to generalize an opinion.With that said, I am changing my vote to ""Yes, I would recommend.""The determining factors are thus:a) The Devs changed the progression model so everything is unlocked now when you purchase the game (you don't need to torture yourself trying to complete the campaign and level up).  I miss this concept so much from the good 'ole days. Pay money, obtain product, no gates.  Beautiful.b) The attention to detail and effort the Devs have put in is actually quite remarkable.  The ""Mouse-Aim"" mode to make this game more approachable without a Joystick.  Physics tweaks. Even down to immersive sound effects. There is nothing I can say that will give you a clear picture of how good this game feels, due to all the polish.c) Business Model.  We're so accustomed to the ""Freemium"" style of games, or subscription based. So seeing a game where each expansion is $60 is a hard pill to swallow.  But it makes sense when you consider this product isn't made for ""bulk"" sales, and doesn't have monthly subscription costs to maintain development.d) Combat aside, just fly around.  It's wonderful!  It takes some getting used to, and if I already wasn't familiar with this style from when I was a kid I can imagine it being incredibly frustrating.When you pull too hard you can hear and feel the turbulence off your wings.  You can feel when your tail is about to stall.  It's more of an art than a science. Even trying to train yourself to go easy on the rudder to prevent crazy jerking, but then mastering how to *use* it instead of *fight* it.The Combat, however, especially on more realistic difficulties, is just a nightmare I'm still trying to figure out.  Just resign that you're not going to hit a thing, and you will immediately be out of ammo. (play quick match with custom settings to have unlimited ammo for training).e) Joystick is a huge plus.  I purchased the Thrustmaster T16000M and it was like night and day for the feel of the game.  In the end, it's a simulator.  It's about the ""feels"". But not a necessity.and most importantly...f) The community -- So incredibly helpful, supportive, and rewarding.So here is what I would recommend for the general user:1) Play World of Warplanes for free.  This is the most arcade flight game you will find. Play it until you are in Tier IV, maybe V.  Just to get familiar with basic flying maneuvers and combat.2) Play War Thunder for free.  Start off with arcade, but then go to ""Realistic"" (not Simulation, which is harder).  ""Realistic"" War Thunder is kinda similar to ""Normal"" campaign settings in IL-2 Campaign mode.  Hud indicators for enemies, but not a lot of hand holding.3) If you are finding that you enjoy ""Realistic"" mode in War Thunder as much, or more than the arcade feel of World of Warplanes, then DEFINITELY consider buying IL-2.  It's like War Thunder ""Realistic"" mode with a bucket of polish.  Added in with the benefit of single-player, and being able to turn on more ""easy-mode"" options if you just want to goof around.The exception to the above statement is if you prefer to play multiplayer games, I think the multiplayer is a smaller playerbase in IL-2, and they tend to play on Simulation difficulty servers. I also am not sure how the Moscow and Kuban expansions will impact you (if that restricts the servers you can join).  So if that's a bit too hardcore for you, then sticking with WoWP and War Thunder might be your best bet.  But if Single-Player is your thing, then IL-2 is a strong candidate!==================================This game is not for casual players, certainly.  I consider myself to be somewhere halfway between Casual and Hardcore in terms of simulators.  Enough that I'll watch 45 minute videos of how to start a plane in complete simulator mode, even if I only play under more casual conditions.However, even with the settings turned as ""Arcade"" as possible, the game is still pretty brutal.  Even in ""Quick Match"" where you can completely customize the options (including physics), the game just feels so clunky.  Both with MouseAim and using my Joystick.Granted, it's probably very true to life.  If you want a super hardcore simulator, you've found it!However, if you:-Want something casual at all-Want a game to relax to-Want to relive the awesomesauce that was the original IL-2 Sturmovik back in 2001 where you could turn the cockpit view off, and play in a completely Arcade Funzone ArenaThen this game is *NOT* for you.I fully support the concept though, there's certainly a place for hardcore simulation players, and this game is great at it! I was just hoping for something closer to a Single-Player version of ""War Thunder""/""World of Warplanes"". Granted, I certainly didn't expect that extreme of cartoon-mode, but I thought I'd be able to enjoy some action with all the ""cheat"" options (Unlimited Ammo, Invulnerability, etc.) like I used to as a kid in the original game.  But even then, it can feel like trying to pilot a washing machine; and yes, I can do it, but it feels more like work than a game to relax to.For the insane price tag, definitely not worth it."
,Recommended,307960,24348038,"Posted: 15 July, 2016",all,Krupinski,"I've played almost every flight sim out there today, and IL-2 is definitely one of my favorites. It's the only one I keep coming back to and have as much fun as I did the first day.While this game is more focused on combat rather than clickable cockpits and other micro management things, I think the flight models, and ""sense of flight"" you get while flying more than make up for some of the things you wish it had. The aircraft feel as if they have weight, and react as if you're actually flying through air. IMO a lot of sims don't design their ""atmosphere"" very well, and because of that it feels like you're flying in a vacuum, not so in IL2.As many of you know, flight sims aren't generally known for having the absolute best graphics out there, but for a sim... the graphics in IL2 are pretty damn good, and I think they've set some sort of precedent with their Kuban map. If you haven't seen the Kuban map just do a quick search on YouTube and you'll know exactly what I mean. All three of the maps, Stalingrad, Moscow, and Kuban are available to anybody in Multiplayer, no matter which version of the game you own.There was a time when you could barely play this game if you had anything less than a GTX 970 and a good processor, even then your frame rates would probably be in the dump. Since then, the devs have made significant optimizations, or graphical improvements in almost every update, even venturing into VR. Nowadays you could probably run this game on a potato and still get 60fps.That's one of the best features of this game IMO, the fact that the devs are always trying to improve the game and listen to their players even while they work on new content. Some devs will leave you in the dark until a new update is released, but these guys post a dev blog every week to show their progress... communication is key to a successful title. Anybody else hyped for the Battle of Midway expansion? ;)Anyways, I could keep going on and on, but I'll stop here for now. I hope this was helpful to somebody out there!"
