76561197992156561,Recommended,307960,17167366,"Posted: 21 July, 2015",all,Souls,"Why this is not a prefect simulation it does have enough good things that I will recommend it.Things I like about it.The flight models are done quite well.  It is a good challenge to fly some of these planes especially a couple of the German ones.  Take offs and landings are not a given,   Each plane fly's differently and are greatly effected by load-out and weight.   The damage model is diverse and can be quite epic at times.  Bomb and gun ballistics seemed accurate.The campaigns are open and that it lets you choose either side.  You can also fly any plane and do any type of mission you want.  You advance the campaigns by completing missions regardless of which side you play or which plane you fly.   As you complete missions you earn upgrades for the aircraft you fly and unlock more airbases to launch from.  I found myself flying planes I would not normally fly because I enjoyed earning the upgrades for them.    The missions let you start in the air close to the objective or can earn more points and do a full mission which includes take off and landing.   It does have a time accel feature but it is 2X only.The ability to play as gunner and bombardier is cool.Quick Mission setups and single missions are availableThe abiltiy to record and replay missions is another nice feature.Things I DislikedThe missions are always the same way-points.  Takeoff, Entry point, Action point, Exit point, Landing.  You can not add or edit any of the way-points.  No mission planning beyond your planes load-out.The friendly AI kind of sucks.  While not totally useless they crash way too much and have trouble keeping up.Non clickable cockpits.Weather effects are kind of bland and the constant winter environment gets old.In summary  IL-2 Sturmovik: Battle of Stalingrad is not my all time favorite but it us good enough to recommend to others who enjoy accurate flight simulations like myself."
