76561198051151584,Recommended,307960,17733789,"Posted: 26 August, 2015",all,robochrist,"Fantastic flight sim. This past year, I have been resurrecting an old passion of mine: Flight Simulation/Space Sim. I grew up flying with my father and my granfather was an experimental test pilot in the USAF. I have been an enthusiast all of my life.Because I cannot afford to fly in real life (due to  both time and money), so I currently fly a Saitek X-52 Pro and a TrackIR5 setup. My 'cockpit' is still in the beginning stages, but I hope to add little by little over time.Even though my own setup is rudimentary at best, this game is still likely one of the most realistic and immersive experiences I've ever had.I highly recommend IL-2: BOS, especially if you are a fan of the franchise. They have improved many facets of the game.The one complaint I have (if I must), is that it kind of boasts a narrow focus. In some ways, that can add to the experience. However, there is also a significant drawback. In an ideal world I would like to see a more varied, fleshed-out campaign/story and more aircraft. If nothing else, I wish 1C Studios would put out more content. Whether that be in the way DCS World does it, Expansions on current titles or something else entirely. Really this Con only speaks to what a fan I am of this franchise. I hope to see more from them in the future.In terms of experience, this came can be slightly brutal at first; even to an experienced pilot (virtual or otherwise). However, if you stick with it, you'll quickly get the hang of it. I Spent a week hitting it hard each night for an hour or two, and finally started to get the basics and get a feel for the aircraft.Anyways, pick the game up, it's great!"
76561197975815323,Recommended,307960,17823189,"Posted: 31 August, 2015",all,machineabuse,"First the negatives;BoS does not support clickable cockpits and have directly stated they will not. Clickable cockpits give a direct visual way to familiarize players with a given interface, especially with the helpfulness of mousing over different elements in the pit to help figure out where things are. This is especially important if you are going to switch between multiple aircraft to deal with the workload. In all honesty had I known that the clickable cockpits were not to be featured I would most likely not have bought it. Had I figured it out sooner I would have had it refunded. It's a personal thing; your mileage may vary.This wouldn't be so bad of course if the mapping for HOTAS setups wasn't so... rigid. My HOTAS Warthog for example would benefit greatly by being able to assign modifier buttons to chord multiple controls to a single hat switch for engine management. BoS as far as I can tell does not allow you to use anything but ALT, SHIFT and CTRL for modifiers. This is a limitation that even War Thunder  doesn't have.BoS has serious issues with configuring any of the multiple position switches on the Warthog to do anything useful.The game also has multiple interface issues that range from annoying to exasperating. From icons in the navigation menu being horrendously cryptic (If you need to exit the game to find out the difference between blue and orange bullets you are designing it wrong.) to old-hat keybinding of 20 keys just to get friendly AI to do anything (Come on guys, commo rose is a modern standard for a reason.).Precious little is known about any sort of mod tools for the game as yet, which would greatly benefit from it's expansion the way that IL2: Cliffs Of Dover has. Also when your most complete manual is written by a 3rd party; you have a serious problem.Aside from that BoS gives a solid simulation experience. The sensation of flight is superb and the level of polish is the highest of any simulation in its class at current. They have done amazing things with the spotting system that sits it head and shoulders above it's contemporaries. Moreso than any other sim is the feeling of being ""in the moment"" above a wintery Russian warzone.Now if only the game would tell me what those stupid bullet colors meant without resorting to the Steam forums."
